{{short description|20th-century English bibliographer and Shakespeare scholar}}
{{more footnotes|date=July 2014}}
'''Sir Walter Wilson Greg''' (9 July 1875 &ndash; 4 March 1959), known professionally as '''W. W. Greg''', was one of the leading bibliographers and [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] scholars of the 20th century.

==Family and education==

Greg was born at [[Wimbledon and Putney Commons|Wimbledon Common]] in 1875. His father, [[William Rathbone Greg]], was an essayist; his mother was the daughter of [[James Wilson (UK politician)|James Wilson]]. As a child, Greg was expected one day to assume editorship of ''[[The Economist]]'', which his grandfather had founded in 1843; Greg was educated at [[Wixenford School|Wixenford]], [[Harrow School|Harrow]] and at [[Trinity College, Cambridge|Trinity College]] of [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]].<ref>{{acad|id=GRG894WW|name=Greg, Walter Wilson}}</ref> At Cambridge he met [[Ronald Brunlees McKerrow|Ronald McKerrow]], whose friendship helped shape Greg's decision to pursue a career in literature. While still in school he compiled a list of Renaissance plays printed before 1700, and he joined the [[Bibliographical Society]] the same year. He was President of the Society from 1930 to 1932<ref>[http://www.bibsoc.org.uk/about/presidents Past Presidents of The Bibliographical Society]</ref> and received its Gold Medal in 1935.<ref>[http://www.bibsoc.org.uk/about/gold-medalists Gold Medalists of The Bibliographical Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127022846/http://www.bibsoc.org.uk/about/gold-medalists |date=2014-01-27 }}</ref>

==Work==

After school, Greg settled into a life of steady productivity, while living on the proceeds of his shares of ''The Economist''. Working in close association with [[A. H. Bullen]], he produced ''Pastoral Poetry and Pastoral Drama'' (1906), the first edited version of the account books of [[Philip Henslowe]] (1906–8) and the papers of [[Edward Alleyn]]. The latter two works provided him with a knowledge of Renaissance theatrical conditions perhaps rivaled only by [[E. K. Chambers]], and this knowledge he applied to the publications of the [[Malone Society]], which he served as general editor between 1906 and 1939. He served as Librarian of Trinity College, 1907–13, resigning after his marriage to his cousin Elizabeth Gaskell. As an independent scholar,  Greg produced editions of ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'' (1910),  [[Robert Greene (16th century)|Robert Greene]]'s ''Orlando Furioso'' and [[George Peele]]'s ''[[The Battle of Alcazar]]'' (published together, 1923), and ''[[Sir Thomas More (play)|Sir Thomas More]]'' (1911). He returned to specific editing with work on ''[[Doctor Faustus (play)|Doctor Faustus]]'' (1950). Greg also wrote on the material conditions of [[English Renaissance theatre|Renaissance theater]] and publishing; his work in this regard includes ''Dramatic Documents from the Elizabethan Playhouses'' (1931) and ''English Literary Autographs, 1550–1650'' (1932). ''The Variants in the First Quarto of King Lear'' (1940) offered a careful examination of this printing. He also wrote hundreds of reviews, including a notably caustic rejection of [[J. Churton Collins]]'s 1905 Oxford edition of Robert Greene.

At the beginning of [[World War II]], Greg moved to [[Sussex]], where he spent the war working on his edition of ''Faustus.'' In addition, he began to prepare his great works of the 1950s: ''The Editorial Problem in Shakespeare'' (1951), ''The Shakespeare First Folio: Its Bibliographical and Textual History'' (1955), ''Some Aspects and Problems of London Publishing, 1550–1650'' (1954), and the essay "The rationale of copy-text" (1950), which had a significant influence on [[textual criticism]]. He was Lyell Reader in Bibliography at Oxford University, 1954–5. Greg was knighted in 1950.

Greg was strongly associated with [[Alfred W. Pollard]] in developing a modern understanding of the transmission of Shakespeare's texts. His greatest achievement{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} is ''A Bibliography of the English Printed Drama to the Restoration,'' published in four volumes between 1939 and 1959.

